= First Visit — The Investigation

The adventure begins in Keshto Village, a frontier settlement in the Venna
Weald clear. The party has arrived in response to a Black Guard contract
issued by the Never-Still.

#flavor[
  Keshto is small and practical --- a cluster of stone and timber buildings
  around a market square, ringed by a low wall that marks the boundary
  between settlement and wilderness. The Weald presses close on all sides,
  ancient forest visible over the rooftops. The air smells of woodsmoke
  and rain.
]

== The Briefing

The party's first contact is Merzaghaal, the Never-Still agent who issued
the contract. He meets them at the village's only inn.

#aloud[
  The Goldenbristle leans forward across the table, his bristled mane
  catching the lamplight. He speaks carefully, as if weighing each word
  against the cost of saying it.

  "Thank you for coming. I will be direct. Over the past three months,
  eleven people have gone missing from the outskirts of this settlement.
  Six civilians --- foragers, a trapper, a courier. Five of our
  peacekeepers, sent to investigate. None have returned. No bodies have
  been recovered.

  "The disappearances cluster along the northeastern routes, where the
  Weald thins and the Fog gets thicker. They are accelerating --- three in
  the last two weeks alone. I have put out a Black Guard contract because
  whatever is happening is beyond what local peacekeepers can handle.

  "Your job is to find out what is taking these people and put a stop to
  it. I can provide what we know, introduce you to the people who know
  more, and offer the resources of this office. Payment on completion."
]

=== Merzaghaal

- *Race:* Goldenbristle (Sootbeast)
- *Faction:* Never-Still (mid-level agent)
- *Personality:* Competent, professional, dry. Cares about this as a faction
  matter first, a humanitarian crisis second. Not callous --- simply
  prioritised. He will be frustrated if the party wastes time.
- *What he knows:* The timeline and geography of the disappearances. That
  the Faerie site northeast of Keshto has cultural significance to the
  Never-Still. That the peacekeepers who were sent were competent and should
  not have simply vanished.
- *What he does not know:* The cause of the disappearances. What is
  happening to the victims. Who is responsible.
- *What he can provide:* The contract briefing, introductions to the Town
  Reeve and the surviving peacekeeper, access to Never-Still records and
  supplies, and a sounding board when the party returns with new
  information.

#note[
  Merzaghaal is the party's anchor NPC. He is not an adventurer and will
  not accompany them into the field, but he is always available in Keshto
  to discuss findings, broker introductions, and provide faction context.
  If the party is stuck, he can suggest next steps --- but he should not
  solve their problems for them.
]

== Investigation Leads

The party can pursue the following leads in any order. Each provides a piece
of the puzzle; together, they give the party enough to head into the field.

=== The Town Reeve

- *Race:* TBD (mortal)
- *Personality:* Harried, worried, practical. The reeve has been dealing
  with panicked families and dwindling search parties for weeks. There may
  be tension with Merzaghaal --- it took dead _peacekeepers_ to get faction
  attention, and the reeve remembers the civilian disappearances that
  preceded them.
- *What the reeve provides:* The human cost of the disappearances. Names,
  dates, occupations, last known locations.

#pftab(
  "Disappearances",
  columns: (2fr, 1fr, 1fr, 2fr),
  [*Name*], [*Occupation*], [*Weeks Ago*], [*Last Seen*],
  [Orin Vasek], [Forager], [11], [Northeast trail, past the creek],
  [Dara Millen], [Trapper], [9], [Her trapline, northeast ridge],
  [Josen Haal], [Courier], [8], [Road to Ashmark, northeast fork],
  [Three civilians], [Various], [6--4], [Northeast outskirts],
  [Two peacekeepers], [Patrol], [3], [Northeast, investigating Vasek route],
  [Three peacekeepers], [Search party], [2], [Northeast, broader search],
  [Pel Torren], [Forager], [1], [Northeast, near the old shrine trail],
)

- *Skill checks:*
  - *Investigate D2:* Review the records and build the timeline. The pattern
    is obvious: every victim was alone or in a small group, every
    disappearance is in the northeast, and the frequency is increasing.
  - *Influence D3:* The reeve opens up about the toll this has taken on the
    community. People are afraid to leave the village. The forager economy
    is suffering. The reeve is grateful someone is finally taking this
    seriously --- or resentful that it took this long.

=== The Surviving Peacekeeper

- *Race:* TBD
- *Personality:* Shaken. He was part of the first two-person patrol sent to
  investigate. His partner vanished. He did not see what happened --- one
  moment his partner was there, the next she was not. He found signs of a
  brief struggle but no body.
- *What he provides:* A specific location --- the area where his partner
  disappeared, which is the party's starting point for finding the dump site
  and/or ritual site. He also provides an emotional anchor: the first taste
  of what the stakes feel like on a personal level.

- *Skill checks:*
  - *Influence D2:* Get him talking. He wants to help but is struggling with
    guilt and fear. A sympathetic approach works better than a demanding one.
  - *Awareness D3:* Notice that he is holding something back --- not
    information, but emotion. His partner was more than a colleague. This is
    not plot-critical, but it adds weight to the stakes.

#note[
  The peacekeeper's key function is to give the party a place to start
  looking. His directions should point them toward the general area where
  both the dump site and ritual site can be found --- northeast of Keshto,
  where the Weald thins and the Fog thickens. Do not make the party roll
  to obtain this information. It is the minimum they need to proceed.
]

=== Early Faerie Site Visit

Merzaghaal may send the party to check the old Faerie shrine northeast of
Keshto as a routine task: "Strange things are happening nearby. Go see if
the old shrine has been disturbed."

#flavor[
  The shrine is a clearing in the deep Weald, marked by standing stones
  overgrown with moss and creeping vines. The air hums faintly --- not a
  sound, exactly, but a resonance you feel in your teeth. Whatever power
  this place once held has faded, but it has not entirely gone.
]

On this first visit, the surface level is exactly what it appears to be:
ancient, overgrown, resonant with faded magic. The party finds nothing
suspicious.

- *Occultism D5:* The character senses that the Faerie resonance here is
  unusually well-preserved --- stronger than it should be for a ruin this
  old. This is flavour, not a clue. It becomes significant only in
  retrospect.
- *Investigate D6:* The character notices subtle signs that someone has been
  here recently --- disturbed moss, a stone shifted slightly out of
  alignment. This DC is intentionally too high for most Tier 1 parties at
  this stage.

#note[
  The shrine is the entrance to Šauhahten's laboratory, but the party
  should not discover this yet. The Investigate D6 is deliberately set
  above what a T1 party can reliably hit --- it exists so that an
  exceptionally lucky or well-built character _might_ get an early hint,
  but the adventure does not require it. If a character does succeed, give
  them a sense that someone has been here, but not enough to find the
  hidden entrance. That requires information from Phase 3.
]

=== A Local Who Remembers

A civilian in Keshto --- a shopkeeper, a supplier --- who interacted with
Šauhahten before he withdrew to the outskirts.

- *Race:* TBD (mortal)
- *Personality:* Curious, not afraid. This person is not involved in the
  plot. They simply remember a remarkable customer. A Mirror is hard to
  forget in a frontier settlement.

- *Finding this NPC:* The party must ask around the village about unusual
  people in the area. *Investigate D3* to locate someone who remembers.
- *What they provide:* A description of Šauhahten --- tall, Mirror features
  (the fey shimmer of an Echo), polite, spoke in measured sentences, asked
  unusual questions about local alchemical supplies and the properties of
  local Fog. Bought materials in bulk: glassware, reagents, heavy metal
  containers. Traveled northeast. Stopped coming to the village perhaps
  six months ago.

#note[
  This NPC is optional in Phase 1. The party can find them now or in Phase
  3 when they return with more specific questions. The information this NPC
  provides becomes much more valuable once the party knows they are looking
  for a Mirror alchemist. In Phase 1, it is a colour detail. In Phase 3,
  it is a confirmation.
]

== Clue Tracker

#note[
  By the end of Phase 1, the party should know:

  - *Thread 1 (the facts):* People are disappearing. The pattern points
    northeast. The disappearances are accelerating.
  - *Thread 2 (partial):* Something strange is happening --- this is not a
    mundane predator or bandit.
  - *A location:* The peacekeeper's directions, pointing them into the
    field.

  If the party has this, they are ready for Phase 2. If they are missing
  the location, the peacekeeper provides it without a check --- it is the
  minimum the adventure requires. Do not let the party get stuck in the
  village.
]

#attention[
  *System lesson for this phase:* Social interaction and skill checks. Let
  the players drive the conversation. Call for rolls only when the outcome
  is uncertain and failure has consequences. If a player asks the reeve
  for the disappearance timeline and the reeve has no reason to hide it,
  just give it to them --- no roll required.
]

= Return to Keshto — The Mortefactor Connection

The party returns to Keshto Village after exploring the dump site and
ritual site. They have new evidence and specific questions: the method is
Mortefactor-derived, the operation is sophisticated and scholarly, and the
perpetrator is not at either field site.

== Merzaghaal Revisited

With the party's new evidence, Merzaghaal's knowledge becomes more useful.

- *Influence D3:* Merzaghaal shares faction intelligence he might otherwise
  keep close. He has heard that an unaffiliated Deathless has been operating
  in the area --- someone who does not belong to any faction he recognises.
  With the party's description of Mortefactor-derived techniques, the pieces
  click. He brokers an introduction to someone who can help.

== The Mortefactor Tracker

A Deathless agent of the Most Ancient and Noble Order of Mortefactors, sent
to quietly track Šauhahten after his expulsion. He has been in or around
Keshto for some time, but lost the trail. The party's evidence from the
ritual site is exactly what he has been looking for.

- *Race:* TBD (Deathless)
- *Faction:* The Most Ancient and Noble Order of Mortefactors
- *Personality:* Guarded, precise, cooperative but with an undercurrent of
  faction loyalty. He wants Šauhahten stopped, but he also wants the
  research recovered --- not destroyed. He views the research as dangerous
  but valuable, and as stolen Mortefactor property.

- *How the party meets him:* Either Merzaghaal brokers the introduction, or
  the tracker approaches the party directly once he hears about their
  findings. He has been waiting for someone to bring him the evidence he
  needs.

- *What he provides:*
  - Šauhahten's name and the circumstances of his expulsion (advocating for
    or already conducting soul experiments)
  - Identification of the ritual techniques as Mortefactor-derived
  - Knowledge of what Prima Materia research requires: Fog proximity and
    ambient magical energy --- exactly what an old Faerie site provides
  - A partial copy of the Faerie resonance cipher that Šauhahten stole when
    he left the order. This is the key to the laboratory entrance.

- *What he wants:*

#attention[
  The tracker wants the research recovered, not simply destroyed. He may
  frame this as a reasonable request --- the Mortefactors can secure it, study
  it safely, ensure it does not fall into other hands. The party may agree,
  disagree, or negotiate. This tension should not derail the adventure, but
  it introduces faction politics at a manageable scale and creates a hook
  for future adventures.

  If the party refuses, the tracker does not become an enemy. He is
  disappointed but pragmatic. If the party agrees, they may have made a
  promise they will want to revisit later.
]

- *Skill checks:*
  - *Awareness D4:* Notice that the tracker has his own agenda. He is
    helpful, but his helpfulness has a direction --- toward recovering the
    research, not just stopping Šauhahten.
  - *Influence D4:* Negotiate the terms of cooperation. A strong result
    gives the party leverage: the tracker agrees to let them decide what
    happens to the research after the laboratory is dealt with.

== A Local Who Remembers (Second Chance)

If the party did not find this NPC in Phase 1, they can find them now with
an *Investigate D2* check (reduced from D3, because the party now has a
specific description to ask about --- a Mirror alchemist who bought unusual
supplies).

The information is the same as in Phase 1, but it now has much more
context. The supply routes and bulk purchases help narrow down the
laboratory's location, confirming what the tracker's knowledge of Prima
Materia requirements already suggests: the Faerie site.

== Putting It Together

#note[
  By the end of Phase 3, the party should know all four investigation
  threads:

  - *Thread 1 (the facts):* People are disappearing. The operation is
    methodical and accelerating.
  - *Thread 2 (the what):* Souls are being extracted using alchemical
    techniques. This is not necromancy, predation, or divine power.
  - *Thread 3 (the who):* Šauhahten, a Mirror, expelled Mortefactor,
    operating alone. He is attempting to create Prima Materia.
  - *Thread 4 (the where):* The laboratory is beneath the old Faerie shrine
    northeast of Keshto --- the site the party may have already visited.

  If the party has all four threads, they are ready for the climax. If they
  are missing Thread 4, the tracker's knowledge of Prima Materia
  requirements (Fog proximity + ambient magical energy) combined with the
  Faerie site's unusual resonance should point them there.
]

== The Moral Question

#attention[
  Before the party enters the laboratory, consider: do they understand why
  Šauhahten is doing what he is doing? The tracker should have explained
  that Prima Materia is the alchemical pinnacle --- a substance that, in
  theory, could restart the broken cycle of death and rebirth. Šauhahten
  believes he is saving the world.

  This matters because the party will have a chance to speak with Šauhahten
  before fighting him, and his argument is genuinely compelling if you do
  not think too hard about the screaming. Prepare for the possibility that
  your players might hesitate, argue among themselves, or even consider
  agreeing with him. That is good --- it means the adventure is working.
  See the Faerie Ruin chapter for guidance on handling this moment.
]
